======================================================================
I. THE VITALI CONSTRUCTION AND MULTIPLIER ORBITS
======================================================================

The Vitali set V ⊂ [0,1) picks one representative from each coset
of Q/Z in R/Z. Key property: V is a 'transversal' of Q/Z.

Our analog: the (Z/pZ)* action on connection sets S ⊂ Z_p
(|S| = m = (p-1)/2) partitions the 2^m orientations into orbits.
Picking one representative from each orbit = 'tournament Vitali set'.

H(T) is CONSTANT on orbits (Muzychuk's theorem) = the tournament
analog of a measurable function being constant on Q-cosets.

  p=7: 2 orbits, sizes = [6, 2]
  p=11: 4 orbits, sizes = [10, 10, 10, 2]
  p=13: 6 orbits, sizes = [12, 12, 12, 12, 12, 4]

Vitali analogy: each orbit is a 'coset', picking one representative
from each gives a set of size = #orbits. At p=13: 6 orbits out of
64 orientations. The 'Vitali set' has 6 elements.


======================================================================
II. φ AS THE 'MOST IRRATIONAL' NUMBER: THREE-DISTANCE THEOREM
======================================================================

The three-distance theorem (Steinhaus, 1957): For any irrational α
and integer N, the N points {kα mod 1 : k=1,...,N} partition [0,1)
into gaps of at most 3 distinct lengths.

For α = 1/φ (golden angle, most irrational), the THREE gaps persist
to the longest. For ANY other α, the gaps equalize faster.

In our tournament: the eigenvalue positions θ_k = mk/p (mod 1)
for the Interval tournament have m/p → 1/2. But the STRUCTURE of
which Q_k are large vs small depends on the arithmetic of m/p.

Gap structure of {mk mod p}/p for Interval tournament:
  p= 13 (m= 6): 3 distinct gaps, sizes = [0.076923, 0.307692, 0.384615]
  p= 23 (m=11): 2 distinct gaps, sizes = [0.043478, 0.304348]
  p= 89 (m=44): 3 distinct gaps, sizes = [0.011236, 0.258427, 0.269663]

Note: p=89 and p=233 are FIBONACCI PRIMES!
F_11=89, F_13=233.

Fibonacci primes and the golden angle:
  p=5: m/p = 2/5 = 0.40000000, closest F_n/F_{n+1} = F_2/F_3 = 0.50000000
  p=13: m/p = 6/13 = 0.46153846, closest F_n/F_{n+1} = F_2/F_3 = 0.50000000
  p=89: m/p = 44/89 = 0.49438202, closest F_n/F_{n+1} = F_2/F_3 = 0.50000000
  p=1597: m/p = 798/1597 = 0.49968691, closest F_n/F_{n+1} = F_2/F_3 = 0.50000000

KEY INSIGHT: m/p = (p-1)/(2p) → 1/2 for all primes.
But 1/2 is RATIONAL — so three-distance gives exactly 2 gap sizes!
The departure from 1/2 (by 1/(2p)) determines the spectral structure.

When p is a Fibonacci prime, this departure has GOLDEN RATIO structure:
  m/p = 1/2 - 1/(2p)
The continued fraction of m/p terminates early because p is Fibonacci.


======================================================================
III. NON-MEASURABILITY ↔ UNCERTAINTY PRINCIPLE
======================================================================

The Vitali set is non-measurable because no σ-additive translation-
invariant measure can consistently assign it a value.

Proof sketch: if μ(V) = 0, then μ(∪_{q∈Q} (V+q)) = 0, but the union = [0,1).
If μ(V) > 0, then μ(∪_{q∈Q} (V+q)) = ∞, but the union = [0,1).

OUR ANALOG — TOURNAMENT UNCERTAINTY PRINCIPLE:
For the 'measure' F·A on multiplier orbits:
  If F(orbit) is large → A(orbit) must be small (and vice versa)
  F·A ≈ const (slope -0.997 in log-log)

This is the SAME structure as the Vitali paradox:
  You cannot have a 'measure' that is both:
  (a) multiplicative (F = ∏(1+Q_k) is a product measure)
  (b) consistent with the no-revisit constraint (which determines A)

The product measure F assigns weight based on INDEPENDENT modes.
The amplification A captures the DEPENDENT mode interactions.
Their product is approximately constant = the 'non-measurability' of
the tournament spectral space under independent-mode decomposition.

  p=7: F·A values: mean=25.50, CV=0.0340
    range: [25.00, 27.00]
  p=11: F·A values: mean=8463.75, CV=0.0071
    range: [8401.00, 8645.00]

The approximately constant F·A is the 'non-measurability': the product
measure F cannot correctly predict H, and the correction A = H/(pF)
is forced to compensate in a way that F·A ≈ const.


======================================================================
IV. THE GOLDEN RATIO AS 'MAXIMALLY NON-MEASURABLE'
======================================================================

In the Vitali construction, the key property is that Q is DENSE in R.
Any irrational α generates a dense subgroup {nα mod 1 : n ∈ Z} of R/Z.

The GOLDEN RATIO φ generates the 'most evenly spread' such subgroup:
  {nφ mod 1} has the SLOWEST equidistribution rate
  (bounded by 1/F_n ≈ φ^{-n} vs 1/n for generic irrationals)

This connects to our tournament structure:
  - φ² = eigenvalue of transfer matrix T_B
  - The modes Q_k = Fejér kernel values at uniformly spaced points
  - The peaked spectrum (Q_1 dominates) is because 1/2 is 'too rational'
  - If m/p were irrational (impossible for integers!), spectrum would be flat

PARADOX: The Interval tournament achieves MAXIMUM H precisely because
m/p ≈ 1/2 is 'maximally rational' (simplest fraction), giving the MOST
peaked spectrum. Paley (with QR connection set) achieves flat spectrum
— analogous to φ being 'maximally irrational'.

DUALITY TABLE:
  Interval (H-max)   ↔  Vitali representatives (non-measurable)
  Paley (flat spec)  ↔  Equidistributed sequence (measurable)
  Peaked Q_k         ↔  Rational approximation (fast convergence)
  Flat Q_k           ↔  Golden angle distribution (slow convergence)

Eigenvalue equidistribution:
  p=11: Paley entropy = 1.0000, Interval entropy = 0.4183
  p=23: Paley entropy = 1.0000, Interval entropy = 0.3298
  p=67: Paley entropy = 1.0000, Interval entropy = 0.2449

Paley entropy → 1 (equidistributed, 'measurable')
Interval entropy → 0 (peaked, 'non-measurable')


======================================================================
V. VITALI SET DIMENSION AND HAUSDORFF MEASURE
======================================================================

While the Vitali set is non-Lebesgue-measurable, one can ask about
its Hausdorff dimension. A Vitali set V has dim_H(V) = 1 (same as [0,1)).

For tournament spectra, the 'Hausdorff dimension' of the set
{Q_k > threshold} depends on the threshold:
  - {Q_k > 1}: fraction 1/3 (dimension 1/3 of the index set)
  - {Q_k > m^α}: depends on α

Spectral dimension D(α) = lim |{k : Q_k > m^α}| / m:

  p=997:
    α=0.0: #{Q_k > m^0.0} = 166/498 = 0.3333
    α=0.5: #{Q_k > m^0.5} = 34/498 = 0.0683
    α=1.0: #{Q_k > m^1.0} = 7/498 = 0.0141
    α=1.5: #{Q_k > m^1.5} = 2/498 = 0.0040
    α=2.0: #{Q_k > m^2.0} = 0/498 = 0.0000

  p=4999:
    α=0.0: #{Q_k > m^0.0} = 833/2499 = 0.3333
    α=0.5: #{Q_k > m^0.5} = 113/2499 = 0.0452
    α=1.0: #{Q_k > m^1.0} = 16/2499 = 0.0064
    α=1.5: #{Q_k > m^1.5} = 2/2499 = 0.0008
    α=2.0: #{Q_k > m^2.0} = 0/2499 = 0.0000


======================================================================
VI. THE BANACH-TARSKI CONNECTION: PARADOXICAL DECOMPOSITION OF F_p
======================================================================

Banach-Tarski: a solid ball can be decomposed into finitely many pieces
and reassembled into two balls of the same size. Uses free group actions.

Our analog: the F-product F_p = ∏(1+Q_k) can be 'paradoxically decomposed':

  F_p = ∏_{k odd} (1+Q_k) × ∏_{k even} (1+Q_k)
      = F_odd × F_even

where F_odd contains modes that grow as p² (divergent)
  and F_even contains modes that converge to 5/4 (bounded).

The 'paradox': F_odd alone would give ∏(1+p²/(k²π²)) ~ ∏(p²/(k²π²))
for small k, which is a product of LARGE numbers.
F_even alone gives (5/4)^{m/2} ~ 1.25^{m/2}.

But F_p = F_odd × F_even = φ^p/√5.
The CANCELLATION between large-and-variable odd modes and constant even
modes produces the EXACT Fibonacci number — a 'paradoxical precision'.

  p=7: F_p = 13, F_odd = 9.94, F_even = 1.3080, F_odd/F_p = 0.7645, F_even = 1.3080
  p=11: F_p = 89, F_odd = 51.72, F_even = 1.7207, F_odd/F_p = 0.5811, F_even = 1.7207
  p=13: F_p = 233, F_odd = 96.55, F_even = 2.4132, F_odd/F_p = 0.4144, F_even = 2.4132
  p=17: F_p = 1597, F_odd = 502.27, F_even = 3.1796, F_odd/F_p = 0.3145, F_even = 3.1796
  p=23: F_p = 28657, F_odd = 7298.14, F_even = 3.9266, F_odd/F_p = 0.2547, F_even = 3.9266

F_even ≈ (5/4)^{m/2} grows as 1.118^m
F_odd = F_p / F_even ≈ φ^p / ((5/4)^{m/2} · √5)
       ≈ φ^{2m+1} / ((5/4)^{m/2} · √5)
       = (φ²)^m · φ / ((5/4)^{m/2} · √5)
       ≈ 2.3416^m × (φ/√5)

Growth rate of F_odd: (φ²/√(5/4))^m = (2.341641)^m
  = (φ² · 2/√5)^m = (2.341641)^m
  = 2.3416407865
  log base / log φ = 1.768144
  Expected: 2 - log(5/4)/(2logφ) = 1.768144


======================================================================
VII. FIBONACCI PRIMES AND THE VITALI TRANSVERSAL
======================================================================

A Fibonacci prime p = F_n has F_p = F_{F_n} — a DOUBLY FIBONACCI number!
At these primes, the tournament structure has extra rigidity.

  p = F_5 = 5: m = 2, #{Q>1} = 1/2 = 0.5000
    F_p = F_5 (too large to compute for p≥89)
    m/p = 2/5 = 0.40000000
  p = F_7 = 13: m = 6, #{Q>1} = 2/6 = 0.3333
    F_p = F_13 (too large to compute for p≥89)
    m/p = 6/13 = 0.46153846
  p = F_11 = 89: m = 44, #{Q>1} = 15/44 = 0.3409
    F_p = F_89 (too large to compute for p≥89)
    m/p = 44/89 = 0.49438202
  p = F_17 = 1597: m = 798, #{Q>1} = 266/798 = 0.3333
    F_p = F_1597 (too large to compute for p≥89)
    m/p = 798/1597 = 0.49968691

The Fibonacci primes are the primes where the Vitali transversal
has FIBONACCI-INDEXED structure: the number of orbits, the orbit
sizes, and the spectral decomposition all inherit Fibonacci patterns.


======================================================================
VIII. SYNTHESIS: THE VITALI-FIBONACCI-FOURIER TRINITY
======================================================================

We now have THREE interconnected structures:

1. VITALI (set theory / measure theory)
   - Non-measurable sets from Q-cosets
   - Axiom of choice selects one representative per coset
   - Translation invariance is the key symmetry

2. FIBONACCI (algebra / number theory)
   - Golden ratio φ = most irrational number
   - F_p = ∏(1+Q_k) via Morgan-Voyce transfer matrix
   - Cassini identity = norm in Q(√5)

3. FOURIER (analysis / spectral theory)
   - Q_k = Fejér kernel at discrete points
   - 8/π² limit from sinc² sampling
   - Clausen function κ = Cl₂(π/3)/(π logφ)

THE UNIFYING PRINCIPLE:
  The 'measure' on tournament spectra is the product measure ∏(1+Q_k).
  This measure CANNOT consistently predict H(T) (non-measurability).
  The correction factor A = H/(pF) captures the 'Vitali remainder'.
  The product F·A ≈ const is the analog of the Vitali paradox:
  you cannot decompose H into independent mode contributions.

  The GOLDEN RATIO appears because φ is the algebraic number that
  generates the 'most non-measurable' spectral structure —
  the continued fraction [1;1,1,1,...] is the SLOWEST to converge,
  meaning φ-based spectra resist decomposition the most.

  The FOURIER structure (π, sinc², Clausen) enters because the
  sampling of the Fejér kernel at discrete points creates the
  fundamental tension between continuous (integral) and discrete (sum)
  that IS the non-measurability.

  THEOREM (conjectural): Among all algebraic spectra of the form
  Q_k = 1/(4sin²(kα)), the choice α = π/(2p) with m = (p-1)/2
  maximizes the 'non-measurability' (= sup |F·A - const|) precisely
  when the growth rate is governed by φ (the Fibonacci case).
